---
import BaseLayout from "../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, medicalWebPageSchema } from "../../../../data/schema.js";

const title = "What Time Should a 6 Year Old Go to Bed?";
const description = "A practical, evidence-based guide to bedtime for 6-year-olds. Covers how much sleep 6-year-olds need, realistic school-night bedtimes, bedtime routines, screen limits, night waking, and when to talk to your pediatrician, based on AAP and AASM guidance.";

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Is 7:00 PM too early for my 6 year old to go to bed?",
    answer: "No—7:00 PM is not too early for many 6-year-olds if wake-up time is early. Children age 6 typically need 9–12 hours of sleep per 24 hours, and a child who wakes around 6:00–7:00 AM may need a 7:00–8:00 PM bedtime to get enough total sleep (AAP, 2016; CDC, 2022). If your child falls asleep easily, wakes reasonably rested, and functions well during the day, that bedtime may be a good fit. If bedtime involves long struggles or your child lies awake for a long time, the schedule may need adjustment. Talk with your pediatrician if your 6-year-old snores, is very hard to wake, or seems tired despite enough time in bed."
  },
  {
    question: "What is a realistic bedtime for a 6 year old on school nights?",
    answer: "A realistic school-night bedtime for many 6-year-olds is about 7:00–8:30 PM, depending on wake time. Most children age 6 need 9–12 hours of sleep, so a child who must wake at 6:30 AM often needs to be asleep by roughly 7:30–9:00 PM to meet recommendations (AAP, 2016). The key is working backward from the morning schedule rather than choosing a bedtime by age alone. A predictable routine also helps children fall asleep on time. Talk with your pediatrician if your child cannot fall asleep within about 30 minutes most nights or has persistent daytime sleepiness."
  },
  {
    question: "Should my 6 year old still be napping?",
    answer: "Most typically developing 6-year-olds no longer need a regular daytime nap, and frequent daytime sleep at this age often suggests insufficient overnight sleep rather than a developmental need for naps (CDC, 2022). Some children may briefly nap after illness, growth spurts, or unusually busy days. If a 6-year-old regularly falls asleep after school, bedtime may need to move earlier. Late naps can also push bedtime later and reduce total nighttime sleep. Talk with your pediatrician if your child seems excessively sleepy, falls asleep in class or the car daily, or snores regularly."
  },
  {
    question: "Why does my 6 year old suddenly fight bedtime?",
    answer: "Bedtime resistance at age 6 is common and is usually related to boundary-testing, fear of missing out, overtiredness, or inconsistent routines rather than a serious sleep problem. School-age children often do best with the same bedtime routine and bedtime every night because predictability supports sleep onset (AAP, 2016; AASM, 2020). Resistance can get worse when screens run late, bedtime shifts on weekends, or children become overtired. Calm limits and a consistent routine usually help more than long negotiations. Talk with your pediatrician if bedtime struggles are severe, prolonged, or paired with anxiety, snoring, or significant daytime behavior changes."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I worry if my 6 year old wakes up at night?",
    answer: "Occasional night waking is common at age 6, especially during stress, illness, nightmares, or schedule changes, but a typically developing 6-year-old should usually be able to return to sleep with minimal help. Repeated night waking becomes more concerning if it happens most nights, leads to daytime tiredness, or is associated with snoring, gasping, leg discomfort, or strong anxiety (AAP, 2016). Keeping the bedtime routine steady and the bedroom quiet and screen-free can help. Talk with your pediatrician if night waking is frequent, worsening, or affecting daytime functioning."
  },
  {
    question: "How long should a bedtime routine be for my 6 year old?",
    answer: "A bedtime routine for a 6-year-old should usually last about 20–30 minutes and follow the same order most nights. Consistent, calming routines help children transition from active evening behavior to sleep and are associated with better sleep onset and fewer bedtime struggles in school-age children (AASM, 2020). A simple routine might include bath or wash-up, pajamas, brushing teeth, one or two books, and lights out. The goal is predictability, not complexity. Talk with your pediatrician if your child cannot settle even with a consistent routine or seems unusually anxious about bedtime."
